        <h1>When the pilot collapses</h1>
        <p class="dek">
          Documented cases of amateurs landing the plane, including attempts
          that ended fatally.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article">
        <section id="intro" aria-labelledby="intro-heading">
          <h2 id="intro-heading" class="visually-hidden">Introduction</h2>
          <p>
            It's a stock movie scene: the pilot slumps over, a terrified
            passenger grabs the controls and a calm voice on the radio talks
            them down. It has happened in real life more than a dozen times,
            almost always in general-aviation aircraft. Some takeover attempts
            have also ended fatally. This record is drawn from the
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk-down_aircraft_landing"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">talk-down landing list</a
            >, accident reports and contemporary news.
          </p>
          <p>
            The cases include genuine non-pilots, students and licensed pilots
            caught in unfamiliar types. Survival depended less on fitting one
            label than on keeping the aircraft controllable and reaching an
            experienced voice. No completely untrained passenger has ever landed
            a large commercial jet. The closest attempt, a fatal one, involved a
            flight attendant who held a commercial pilot license but wasn't
            qualified on the aircraft (
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helios_Airways_Flight_522"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">Helios Flight 522</a
            >).
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="successes" aria-labelledby="successes-heading">
          <h2 id="successes-heading">The survivable landings</h2>
          <ol class="case-list">
            {
              successes.map((entry) => (
                <li class="case" id={entry.id}>
                  <header class="case-header">
                    <p class="case-meta">
                      <time>{entry.when}</time>
                      <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
                      <span>{entry.where}</span>
                    </p>
                    <h3>{entry.passenger}</h3>
                    <p class="case-tags">
                      <span class={`tag tag-${entry.outcome}`}>
                        {outcomeLabels[entry.outcome]}
                      </span>
                      <span class="tag">{experienceLabels[entry.experience]}</span>
                      {entry.aircraft && (
                        <span class="tag tag-aircraft">{entry.aircraft}</span>
                      )}
                    </p>
                  </header>
                  <div class="case-body" set:html={entry.body} />
                </li>
              ))
            }
          </ol>
        </section>

        <section id="failures" aria-labelledby="failures-heading">
          <h2 id="failures-heading">The fatal takeover attempts</h2>
          <p>
            Failures are far harder to document, which matters for reading the
            list above. A fatal crash usually leaves investigators unable to
            tell whether a passenger recognized the incapacitation, reached the
            controls, consciously tried to fly or merely disturbed the controls
            while trying to help. Successful passengers can describe what they
            did, controllers keep recordings and the aircraft survives for
            examination. In a fatal uncontrolled crash, an amateur takeover
            attempt may simply be unknowable. The public record carries heavy
            survivorship bias.
          </p>
          <p>
            Two well-documented takeover attempts ended with passenger or crew
            fatalities.
          </p>
          <ol class="case-list">
            {
              failures.map((entry) => (
                <li class="case case-failure" id={entry.id}>
                  <header class="case-header">
                    <p class="case-meta">
                      <time>{entry.when}</time>
                      <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
                      <span>{entry.where}</span>
                    </p>
                    <h3>{entry.passenger}</h3>
                    <p class="case-tags">
                      <span class={`tag tag-${entry.outcome}`}>
                        {outcomeLabels[entry.outcome]}
                      </span>
                      <span class="tag">{experienceLabels[entry.experience]}</span>
                      {entry.aircraft && (
                        <span class="tag tag-aircraft">{entry.aircraft}</span>
                      )}
                    </p>
                  </header>
                  <div class="case-body" set:html={entry.body} />
                </li>
              ))
            }
          </ol>
          <p>
            NTSB files also hold fixed-wing incapacitation crashes in which the
            aircraft was lost with others aboard, usually involving
            high-performance types, high altitude or depressurization, where
            nobody reached the controls or the radio in time.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="airliner" aria-labelledby="airliner-heading">
          <h2 id="airliner-heading">
            Why passengers fare better in small planes
          </h2>
          <p>
            There is no verified case of a completely untrained passenger
            landing a large commercial jet. A simulator shows that a novice can
            succeed under ideal coaching, but real airline operations rarely
            put a passenger in those conditions.
          </p>
          <p>
            Airliners carry two qualified pilots and sometimes relief crews.
            When a
            <a
              href="https://apnews.com/article/idaho-boise-ff61891effb14a1c833f0f0ec5b7fe15"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">United 737 captain</a
            >
            had a heart attack on a Houston–Seattle flight in 2013, the flight
            diverted to Boise; an off-duty United pilot onboard assisted, and
            the airplane landed safely with the remaining qualified crew. The
            On a
            <a
              href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/pilot-another-airline-helps-land-southwest-flight-captain-falls-ill-rcna76275"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">2023 Southwest flight</a
            >
            that returned to Las Vegas and a
            <a
              href="https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/newark-halifax-flight-boston-captain-medical/3970960/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">2026 PAL Airlines</a
            >
            diversion into Boston, the remaining qualified pilot also landed.
            Simultaneous incapacitation is vanishingly rare. When it results
            from hypoxia or airborne contaminants, a replacement may be impaired
            too. That happened on Helios 522.
          </p>
          <p>
            A passenger would also need to operate an unfamiliar cockpit. When
            <a
              href="https://mythresults.com/episode94"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">MythBusters tested</a
            >
            the scenario in its December 2007 <cite>Airplane Hour</cite>. Adam
            Savage and Jamie Hyneman each tried to land a simulated Boeing 747
            with no preparation and both crashed. On a second attempt, each
            landed safely while a licensed pilot gave step-by-step radio
            instructions. The show rated the claim "plausible," not confirmed:
            it was a simulator demonstration with the instructor immediately
            available and no real consequences for the failed first try. With
            coaching, both novices operated the prepared simulator. A passenger
            in flight would first have to diagnose and configure an unfamiliar
            airliner. Boeing and Airbus cockpits differ enough that professional
            pilots need type training.
          </p>
          <p>
            Autoland won't rescue you either. It exists, but it requires a
            certified aircraft, specific instrument-landing infrastructure at
            the airport and pilots to program and monitor it. It accounts for a
            small minority of airline landings and can't be set up by a novice
            from cruise. The episode's suggestion that a modern jet's autopilot
            could simply land by itself blurred ordinary autopilot with
            autoland: conventional airline autoland still requires the crew to
            configure and supervise it. Small planes mostly have no autoland at
            all; Garmin's emergency system on some new light aircraft is a
            different, recent exception. In the real cases above, autopilot
            bought time in cruise at best. Every touchdown in this record was
            hand-flown; in Harrison's case the collapse knocked the autopilot
            off and turned a stable cruise into a dive.
          </p>
          <p>
            Taking over a general-aviation aircraft is a narrower problem.
            Duplicate controls are within reach, approach speeds are lower and
            the plane is often stable in cruise. Controllers can clear traffic
            and choose a long runway. The standard is a survivable touchdown,
            not a professional landing. In nearly every survivable case here, a
            calm instructor, controller or experienced pilot was available by
            radio.
          </p>
          <p>
            A Caravan or King Air is much more complex than a basic
            trainer. White and Kinane-Wells had to manage that complexity on
            their first flights in those aircraft. The easier cases involved a
            docile light aircraft, daylight and a working radio.
            Darkness, bad weather, speed, radio failure and helicopter controls
            make the task harder.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="how-often" aria-labelledby="how-often-heading">
          <h2 id="how-often-heading">Frequency of pilot incapacitation</h2>
          <p>
            Rarely. An
            <a
              href="https://www.atsb.gov.au/sites/default/files/media/32864/b20060170.pdf"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">ATSB research report</a
            >
            found 98 medical or physiological pilot-incapacitation events
            between 1975 and March 2006, ten of them fatal. All ten fatal
            accidents were single-pilot operations, killing 24 people. A later
            <a
              href="https://www.atsb.gov.au/publications/2015/ar-2015-096"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer">ATSB study</a
            >
            covering 2010 to 2014 counted about 23 reported incapacitation
            occurrences a year, roughly one per 34,000 flights in high-capacity
            transport, most of them gastrointestinal illness. The leading cause
            of actual in-flight pilot death in single-pilot operations is
            cardiovascular disease. In US general aviation, incapacitation
            causes only a handful of accidents in a typical year, and in most of
            those nobody else is aboard.
          </p>
        </section>

        <aside class="takeaways" aria-labelledby="takeaways-heading">
          <h2 id="takeaways-heading">If you're a passenger</h2>
          <ol>
            <li>
              Press the radio's transmit button and say <strong>mayday</strong>.
            </li>
            <li>
              Emergency frequency <strong>121.5</strong>; squawk
              <strong>7700</strong>.
            </li>
            <li>Hold the wings level until ATC takes over.</li>
            <li>
              Take an AOPA
              <a
                href="https://aopa.org/training-and-safety/online-learning/safety-spotlights/pinch-hitter"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer">pinch-hitter course</a
              >
              before an emergency.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </aside>
      </article>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>

